node.accessibility_caption: A student stands outside in front of a stone building and a black iron railing

node.text:
“Because my parents are Bengali immigrants from India, the effects [of 9/11] were felt differently in my family,” said Will Dey ’23, a joint concentrator in physics and computer science. “My parents had to explain how being brown was associated with terrorism, and we were often ‘randomly’ checked at airport security. All of that was hard to put together as a kid, because there was a lot of stigma against brown people," he said. "In school, we were just taught that we were at war with a big unseen enemy, and it was always shrouded in mystery. I think that has had some far-reaching effects, which can be felt today.”⠀
⠀
#Harvard #September11⠀
⠀
Photo: Jon Chase/Harvard Staff Photographer⠀
⠀
---⠀
Harvard College students, who are among the nearly quarter of the American population who were either not alive or are too young to remember 9/11, share how the day nevertheless affected their lives. Read more stories at the link in our bio.

node.accessibility_caption: A student stands outside with green leaves behind her

node.text:
“I want to work in public service and understanding events in the past is really critical to that,” said Jahnavi Rao ’22, a government concentrator from Philadelphia. “I’m inspired by the resilience of the American people after 9/11, and it really showed me that there are ways for all Americans to come together and do really great things to support each other. We can take a lot of pride in that and learn a lot of lessons from it.”⠀
⠀
#Harvard #September11⠀
⠀

While in high school, Zoree Jones ’24, who was born a few months after 9/11 and grew up near Washington, D.C., met local first responders at a 9/11 memorial event. “I realized that these first responders reflected the community of folks who were so instrumental on that day,” she said. “I was moved to remember the courage of people who ran into the buildings while others ran out.”⠀
⠀
#Harvard #September11⠀

“If you’re growing up with security measures at airports and large public spaces, and there are some people around who are afraid of tall buildings, it feels normal, like it’s always been this way,” said Michael Cheng ’22, who is pursuing a joint concentration in history and mathematics and a concurrent fourth-year master’s degree in computer science. “It’s kind of strange to live that reality and also know that it hasn’t been like this for that long.”⠀
⠀

“My mom was pregnant with me during 9/11, and my father, who was an Air Force pilot for 23 years, was flying an 8 a.m. commercial shuttle from Boston to La Guardia that day,” said Caitlin Beirne ’24, a Theater, Dance & Media concentrator from Long Island. “He turned around the World Trade Center towers about six minutes before the first tower was hit.” Soon after the events of 9/11, he was deployed to the Middle East for six years.⠀
⠀
#Harvard #September11⠀

node.accessibility_caption: A man wearing a mask cleans the back of a statue

node.text:
Harvard Yard’s most popular resident, the John Harvard Statue, is nearing 140 years old. Enduring New England weather, excited visitors, and occasional vandals, the iconic statue receives occasional washings by Harvard’s Landscape Services team. But this summer he underwent a careful restoration: a team specializing in the restoration of public monuments restored the original color and shine to the 1884 statue. ⠀
⠀
“We think of the John Harvard Statue as being a kind of stable, forever monument, but this bronze is actually a delicate work of art,” said Angela Chang, a specialist in the conservation of objects and sculpture at the Harvard Art Museums. ⠀
⠀
Check out our Story for a behind-the-scenes look at the restoration of the statue.⠀
⠀
#Harvard #JohnHarvardStatue⠀
⠀
Photos: @stephanie_blair_mitchell/Harvard Staff Photographer
